SIMPLE: infusion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infusion
<hw>In*fu"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>infusio</ets> a pouring in: cf. F. <ets>infusion</ets>. See
<er>Infuse</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
infusing, pouring in, or instilling; instillation; <as>as, the
<ex>infusion</ex> of good principles into the mind; the
<ex>infusion</ex> of ardor or zeal.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our language has received innumerable elegancies and improvements
from that <qex>infusion</qex> of Hebraisms.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is infused; suggestion;
inspiration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His folly and his wisdom are of his own growth, not the echo or
<qex>infusion</qex> of other men.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of plunging or dipping into a fluid;
immersion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Baptism by
<xex>infusion</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jortin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Pharmacy)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The act or
process of steeping or soaking any substance in water in order to
extract its active principles.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The liquid
extract obtained by this process.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sips meek <qex>infusion</qex> of a milder herb.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infusionism</ent>⟦br⟧
